
City revenue (TBD)
------------------

Municipal income sources to implement alongside assets, homes, and infrastructure capacity.

Asset taxes
    Non-exempt owners pay tax on productive assets (offices, factories, workshops, etc.).
    Tax scales with asset level and monthly output — not a separate upkeep line item.

    When infrastructure demand exceeds Q.infrastructure_capacity, taxed assets stop
    paying: owners in overloaded districts (or citywide, if demand is aggregated) lose
    that revenue stream until capacity catches up. Rubble / offline assets already
    pay nothing.

    The Big Three megacorps are mostly tax-exempt on their holdings; syndicates,
    cooperatives, first/second-wave neighborhoods, and (eventually) shareholder-rich
    local capital bear the brunt. That gives the player a reason to prioritize
    infrastructure in less corporate districts — Aurora, Pitts, Deeps — where asset
    taxes actually fund the budget.

Other revenue (sketch)
    Longshore and tourism (see economic_tick_planning.md)
    Fines, permits, seized assets
    Refusal-to-pay during infra deficit as a visible budget shock in Status
